4 <a href="javascript:card_browser(245)">Aragorn, King in Exile</a> (Premium) <br>
3 Gandalf, The Grey Pilgrim (Premium) <br>
Arwen, Elven Rider <br>
Gimli, Dwarf of the Mountain Race (Premium) <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(193)">Sam, Son of Hamfast</a> <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(185)">Merry, From O&#39;er the Brandywine</a> <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(164)">Thrarin, Dwarven Smith</a> <br>
Filibert Bolger, Wily Rascal <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(170)">Bounder</a> <br>
4 <a href="javascript:card_browser(179)">Hobbit Stealth</a> <br>
2 <a href="javascript:card_browser(180)">Hobbit Sword</a> <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(194)">Sting</a> (Rare) <br>
Bill the Pony <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(197)">There and Back Again</a> <br>
3 <a href="javascript:card_browser(8)">No Stranger to the Shadows</a> <br>
2 <a href="javascript:card_browser(11)">Ranger&#39;s Sword</a> <br>
2 <a href="javascript:card_browser(303)">Armor</a> <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(304)">Athelas</a> <br>
3 <a href="javascript:card_browser(15)">Swordsman of the Northern Kingdom</a> <br>
 <br>
The Balrog, Flame of Udun (Rare) <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(125)">Ulaire Enquea, Lieutenant of Morgul</a> <br>
2 <a href="javascript:card_browser(127)">Ulaire Nertea, Messenger of Dol Guldur</a> <br>
4 Isengard Warrior <br>
4 Isengard Shaman <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(966)">Goblin Flankers</a> <br>
4 <a href="javascript:card_browser(73)">Goblin Scavengers</a> <br>
<a href="javascript:card_browser(80)">Goblin Warrior</a> <br>
3 <a href="javascript:card_browser(86)">Moria Scout</a> <br>
2 <a href="javascript:card_browser(969)">Goblin Scrabbler</a> <br>
4 <a href="javascript:card_browser(72)">Goblin Runner</a> <br>
4 <a href="javascript:card_browser(75)">Goblin Scimitar</a> <br>
3 <a href="javascript:card_browser(82)">Host of Thousands</a> <br>
2 <a href="javascript:card_browser(91)">They Are Coming</a> <br>
 <br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> One of the things I&#39;ve been meaning to do for a long time is create a good inexpensive deck.  One of my tournament decks runs over 35 rares, and the other&#39;s up there as well.  People have said &quot;you can build a deck that competes with just a few rares&quot;, and that&#39;s true.  But I wanted to win.  So a few days of planning and testing came up with this approach, which went 4-0 at a local tournament and also wins about half the times against the $400 decks.  So how does it work?  Like First National Change Bank, Volume, my friends, Volume.<br>
<br>
Shadow: I considered Isengard Orcs here (my build runs 3 Orc Commanders as its only rares), but liked Moria more.  I knew I would have to replace Goblin Armory and Cave Trolls, along with other tricks like Goblin Swarms and Relics of Moria.  Moria traditionally has two problems: archery, especially directed, and PATHS.  With Realms, a really quick solution arose to the first problem: Isengard Warrior.  Get him and one other Isengard Orc in play, and all Aragorn&#39;s Bow does is ping a pointless Shaman while Rumil and Gondor Bowmen stand by helplessly.  The 2 and 3 vitality sop up the undirected points.  Furthermore, Shamans are cheap (and Warriors not that expensive at 3, site 4 roaming) and they&#39;re minions with strength.<br>
That points to the other strength of this deck: it&#39;s hard to run out of minions.  There are 27 bodies in this deck, and 8 ways to get more.  Even the 4 cards that don&#39;t get minions draw a card.  Dropping five minions per move starting at site 4 is quite common.  Eventually you&#39;ll break through.  By focusing on bodies, this deck avoids the bane of Goblin Armories everywhere, Sleep Caradhras.  Most people won&#39;t take out just a They are Coming, assuming the Armories are there.  Good.  Even if they do, 3 Twilight and an exertion means more people.  Whoo hoo.<br>
The Nazgul punish big fellowships.  Try to save Nertea for a big push, if possible, but be unafraid to use Enquea early.  Nertea can get the gun again if need be - and it happens more often than you think.<br>
Unfortunately, PATHS is still a problem.  If you play in an area with lots of PATHS but not much archery, swap out 2 Isengard minions for 2 Saurman&#39;s Snows, to play at the right time.  Both is a little tricky.  Choosing the proper person to overwhelm is important; I almost never go for Frodo first if there&#39;s any whiff of Frodo&#39;s Power around.  I suggest Sam, then Legolas / Aragorn / Gandalf.  4 or 5 victorious minions means no double move anyway.  Always assign extra minions to overwhelm, even if it&#39;s someone like Arwen.  You won&#39;t win many one-on-one skirmishes here, but companions die when attacked by 4 Orcs.  A lot.<br>
<br>
Fellowship: This deck is designed to play quickly.  Boromir is the most important rare in the deck; his job is to take the big minions early, until you can find more companions to throw in the way.  Almost every card has multiple targets (Hobbit Swords, Hobbit Stealth, No Strangers, Swordsman) and should be played quickly, especially early in the game.  This is NOT a super Gandalf deck that hoards Servants.  Use the Stealths early, win the skirmishes when you can, find more minions and useful cards. Aragorn&#39;s role is the one to win the occasional &quot;big skirmish&quot;, which is why he has two swords and 3 pumpers.  Arwen&#39;s ability is quite useful late in the game, to remove cards of the type you don&#39;t want off an archery wound or the like.  In general, don&#39;t be afraid to sacrifice companions - that&#39;s why there are so many.  Even if everybody but Sam dies (and it happens), you win.<br>
Bidding is tricky; I normally bid 2 or 3, and choose to go first if I win.  My meta is low-burden, and more mixed than most, with plenty of Nazgul and even a little Sauron to punish high burden bidders.  In other areas, you may need to bid a bit more.  Going first is preferable, even if (often, really) you stop at 2.  Giving up initiative early isn&#39;t bad, because you can set up a killer hand for site 4.  Once you get the companions, get rolling!  You&#39;ll get a stop in Moria, most likely. Decent planning usually gives you the stop at your site 7 - and a hand emptying often gets you one at the Shores as well.  Mulligan aggressively, based on what you&#39;re doing; I probably mulligan about half the time.  This deck plays fast enough to barely notice two cards early, and getting the right six is much better.<br>
This deck is set up for my meta, which is very mixed.  There are a few cards that can be changed, depending on what you see.<br>
Uruks and Nazgul: Pull Sting.  The best substitute is Flaming Brand (Aragorn is 13, with 3 possible pumpers). Another option - a more Uruk build - is Blade of Gondor, if you have it.  Another really good option is a second Filibert (for a Stealth, most likely) which lets your hobbits back you up against those annoying Savageries and fierce Wraiths.  The twilight reduction will keep the pain down somewhat.  If I know the opponent&#39;s deck, I&#39;ve been known to mulligan to look for Filibert.<br>
Pure Moria or Sauron Orc Bowmen: Change Sting to a Frying Pan, and swap a Swordsman and Athelas for 2 Sleep Caradhras.  Use them only as a last resort (since you&#39;ll likely take out some twilight removal too), but it&#39;s the stopper described above.  A more gutsy call would be Deep in Thought, which I really haven&#39;t tried.  I&#39;d love to hear if anybody takes a shot with it.  Play Rumil instead of Filibert if you like - but kill him at site 6, and think about dumping Arwen, to avoid free Moria Scouts.<br>
<br>
I&#39;d love comments, but please try to keep to the 3-rare rule.  A few more rares would help, but that&#39;s not the main point; it&#39;s to make an effective and inexpensive deck.  Before you ask, most Gandalf signet companions are rare (Pippin, Merry, Frodo, Aragorn, Arwen, Gimli), so Trust Me isn&#39;t that effective.  In any event, may all your journeys be pleasant ones. </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font class="bfont"> <a href="/lotr/decks/decks.php">Back to Decks Directory</a> | <A HREF="/lotr/decks/decks.php?reviews=25937"> Read Reviews </A> | <a href="deckprint.php?deck=25937" TARGET="BLANK_"> Printer Friendly</a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><a name="review"></a><font class="h2font">In order to review decks you must be a registered member. <A href="/lotr/main/join.php">Sign up for free!</A></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
